{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531346"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:13:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14589"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14589"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.27,0.03,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57197"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7282"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14589"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42656"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"133"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3475"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17792"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44722"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57197"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with increasing confusion over three days. He has a history of alcohol-related cirrhosis and has continued to drink heavily. His medical history includes oesophageal varices and ascites. He takes spironolactone and propranolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 98/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. He is confused and has asterixis. His abdomen is distended with shifting dullness. There are spider naevi on his chest.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of blood test results is most likely in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Albumin 42 g/L (35-50), ALT 450 U/L (5-40), INR 1.1 (0.9-1.2), BSL 5.5 mmol/L (3.5-7.8)","Albumin 38 g/L (35-50), ALT 85 U/L (5-40), INR 1.3 (0.9-1.2), BSL 12.2 mmol/L (3.5-7.8)","Albumin 22 g/L (35-50), ALT 380 U/L (5-40), INR 1.2 (0.9-1.2), BSL 6.2 mmol/L (3.5-7.8)","Albumin 45 g/L (35-50), ALT 55 U/L (5-40), INR 2.5 (0.9-1.2), BSL 5.8 mmol/L (3.5-7.8)","Albumin 18 g/L (35-50), ALT 65 U/L (5-40), INR 2.8 (0.9-1.2), BSL 2.8 mmol/L (3.5-7.8)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with hepatic encephalopathy in the setting of decompensated chronic liver disease. The clinical features of asterixis, confusion, and known cirrhosis with portal hypertension (varices, ascites) suggest end-stage liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin 18 g/L, ALT 65 U/L, INR 2.8, BSL 2.8 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E represents the most likely pattern in end-stage liver disease. The low albumin reflects impaired synthetic function, while the modestly elevated ALT is typical as there is little functioning hepatic tissue remaining to release transaminases. The elevated INR reflects impaired synthesis of clotting factors, and the low blood sugar results from impaired gluconeogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin 42 g/L, ALT 450 U/L, INR 1.1, BSL 5.5 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E would be more consistent with acute hepatitis, where synthetic function is preserved (normal albumin and INR) but there is significant hepatocellular injury (markedly elevated ALT).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin 38 g/L, ALT 85 U/L, INR 1.3, BSL 12.2 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows relatively preserved synthetic function and would be unusual in someone with clinical evidence of decompensated cirrhosis. The high BSL would be unexpected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin 22 g/L, ALT 380 U/L, INR 1.2, BSL 6.2 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows an inconsistent pattern - the low albumin suggests chronic disease but the normal INR does not fit with significant synthetic dysfunction. The markedly elevated ALT would be unusual in end-stage disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbumin 45 g/L, ALT 55 U/L, INR 2.5, BSL 5.8 mmol/L\u003C/strong\u003E shows a contradictory pattern with normal albumin but elevated INR. In chronic liver disease, both synthetic functions would typically be affected together.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn chronic liver failure, the characteristic pattern is impaired synthetic function (low albumin, elevated INR), relatively modest elevations in transaminases, and a tendency toward hypoglycaemia. This reflects the loss of functioning hepatic tissue and the liver\u0027s diminished capacity to perform its synthetic and metabolic functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In chronic liver failure, synthetic function is impaired leading to decreased albumin and elevated INR.","Transaminases may be only mildly elevated in end-stage liver disease as there is little functioning liver tissue remaining.","Hypoglycaemia can occur in end-stage liver disease due to impaired gluconeogenesis."],"references":["Sharma A, Nagalli S. Chronic Liver Disease. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK554597/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42656"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14589"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42656"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T11:30:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T11:31:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7282"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57197"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}